You don't have to be an anchorman to #AnchorDown and help the Lafayette Commodores win the 2020 Crosstown Classic United Way Challenge! Every dollar makes a difference as we partner together with our outstanding school districts to make a significant impact throughout our community.

To support Lafayette County School District, you can donate online at www.unitedwayoxfordms.org/dores. In addition, Commodore fans can text ‚ÄúDORES‚Äù to 40403 and then click on the link they will receive prompting them to complete their donation. Finally, donations can also be mailed or delivered to our office in Suite 5 of the Baker Building (440 N. Lamar Blvd. in Oxford). If no one is there, simply stick the contribution through the mail slot.

The pledged donation must be collected by 11:59 p.m. on Wednesday, September 16, 2020, in order for the amount to count towards this year‚Äôs competition. You can learn more about the challenge at unitedwayoxfordms.org/crosstown. #TheCounty #LafayetteCountyMS #InvestInLOU

shared_text:
Mud & Magnolias
August 10 at 6:15 PM ¬∑

üçé MEET THE EDUCATORS üçé
Hannah Gadd Ardery is a choir, music history and dual-credit music appreciation teacher at Lafayette High in City of Oxford. And, she's received the honor of being Mississippi's Teacher of the Year.
She comes from a family of teachers (and even married a teacher), and say's she's a ‚Äúproduct of the ‚Äò90s; like, golden age of Disney and the golden age of all things pop music; I mean, Britney (Spears) was and still is my queen.‚Äù
Sure, she teaches about music and choir, but she says her favorite part of her job is teaching students to love one another. "Until you intentionally include, you unintentionally exclude, and they really understand that and they understand the value of loving each other.‚Äù
Read more about Ardery here: https://mudandmagnolias.com/teacher-of-the-year-hannah-gadd-ardery-lafayette-high-school/

üçé MEET THE EDUCATORS üçé
Hannah Gadd Ardery is a choir, music history and dual-credit music appreciation teacher at Lafayette High in City of Oxford. And, she's received the honor of being Mississippi's Teacher of the Year.
She comes from a family of teachers (and even married a teacher), and say's she's a ‚Äúproduct of the ‚Äò90s; like, golden age of Disney and the golden age of all things pop music; I mean, Britney (Spears) was and still is my queen.‚Äù
Sure, she teaches about music and choir, but she says her favorite part of her job is teaching students to love one another. "Until you intentionally include, you unintentionally exclude, and they really understand that and they understand the value of loving each other.‚Äù
Read more about Ardery here: https://mudandmagnolias.com/teacher-of-the-year-hannah-gadd-ardery-lafayette-high-school/

post_text: We have celebrated some highs and unfortunate lows this week, but nevertheless, we came back together after months apart. This picture is not about buses going home with kids after a successful day, but it‚Äôs a scene that happened around 2:30 pm today. This is our baseball coach. Normally, coaches are anxious to get their athletes out on the field, dressed and ready to go. Today, Coach Walker sat his team down and had a conversation about character. Not for the camera, not for social media, but for his boys. At Lafayette, we believe in a complete education. We are blessed to have teachers that love their calling and take the time for the important things. This is why this week, we felt like we came home to family. Stay Anchored.

post_text: Congratulations Aubrey Claire N.!!
shared_text:
Loidha Castillo Bautista is at Lafayette High.
June 17 at 4:55 PM ¬∑ Oxford, MS ¬∑

My students work hard! Let me tell you about this picture.

This is Aubrey Claire. She will be a senior, and she‚Äôs been a photographer for three years. Many of her pictures have been featured as part of the Commodore Media Group. She‚Äôs won awards for her work.
For the past year and a half, she‚Äôs been trying to get one of her images to be picked by Herff Jones as one of the landing pages for their yearbook website. She would send them pictures after every photo shoot she edited. For a year and a half! Today, it paid off.

She can now say she‚Äôs an internationally published photographer. Her name is at the bottom. LHS and Oxford, MS are also part of the caption.

She put Lafayette County School District on the map. She‚Äôs talented, but I‚Äôm so proud of her determination to see this through and get it done!
#AnchoredToExcellence #TheCounty Herff Jones

Today, Lafayette seniors opened their door to a surprise. LHS faculty and staff drove out to every corner of the county and hand-delivered a yard sign for each senior enrolled at Lafayette. They wrote personalized notes on the back of each of the signs to show their support and love.

Each sign was purchased by the LHS BETA Club as a gift for the seniors and faculty eagerly volunteered to deliver the signs. Here's to you, seniors. Stay Anchored to Excellence.

April 14, 2020, 3:00 PM. During a press conference today, Governor Tate Reeves mandated that school buildings remain closed for the remainder of the semester. This does not suspend the rest of the term. LCSD will continue with distance learning and requirements to finish out the school year. Meals will also continue to be provided to our students at the pick-up locations.

We will provide you with more information soon regarding grade promotions and graduation. Continue to follow our website and social media accounts for more information.

post_text:
During the end of the third nine weeks, fourth graders at LUES paired up and researched a country. They wrote a research paper, made a flag, created an Adobe Spark video, came up with a costume representing their country, and a food dish popular to that country. They finished the projects but the dress up and food events were to be presented after our return from Spring Break. They were looking forward to their return for the presentation, but instead, they dressed up at home and submitted their picture.

We have to say they nailed it!

post_text:
Tonight, the Commodore family mourns the passing of the wonderful Mrs. Gale Wright Arrington. The Arrington name is forever tied to the halls and history of our great schools, and Mrs. Arrington was its voice. Thank you for your many years of service to LHS. Our deepest condolences to the Arrington and Wright Families.

"Born in Water Valley, MS to the late W. E. Wright, Sr. and Elizabeth Baddley Wright, Mrs. Arrington was the receptionist at Lafayette County High School. She loved her job and her favorite words in life were the words she said the most as she answered the phone, 'Lafayette High School.'"

Meet Captain Slam-O created by Jackson. He‚Äôs one of the best superheroes of all time. He gets stronger every day by eating healthy foods and taking his vitamins. He‚Äôs on a mission to fight the Coronavirus by slamming it out of this world!

Alex created a Zombenette with sloth-like arms. She drags her arms when she walks, so she's too slow to eat anyone's brains.
#distancelearning #creators #brainpower

post_text:
UPDATE: March 19, 2020 1:00 PM

As per the mandate of Governor Tate Reeves, Lafayette County schools will remain closed until April 17, 2020. In response, the Mississippi Board of Education moved to cancel state testing for this school year.

Decisions are being made daily, and even hourly. We continue to stay anchored to serving our students and community.

We are working on plans to move forward with your child's education and will be providing information soon. Teachers are beginning to reach out to gather more information, please respond as soon as possible.

Your safety and your child's education and well-being is our top priority. Please know that we miss them and will continue to work hard for them in the coming days. Stay safe and stay "Anchored to Excellence."

If you have any questions--or if you have information you would like to share regarding out-of-school time activities in the Oxford-Lafayette-University community--please contact Sarah McClellan (lafayetteliteracy@gmail.com) or Tamara Hillmer (tlhillmer@oxfordsd.org).

We will continue to assess the situation and update you on future Out-of-School Time Coffee Hour meetings as soon as possible.

Thank you for understanding, and for your continued support of the LOU community.

Lafayette County Literacy Council
United Way of Oxford-Lafayette County
Oxford Park Commission

Oxford, MS (Feb. 25, 2020) - Congratulations to our very own Sarah Harmon. Tonight she was named the 2020 Youth Character Award winner for Lafayette Schools.

She received the award at the annual Lafayette County Law Enforcement Association banquet. Sarah opened the banquet with a beautiful rendition of the national anthem. The Lafayette High School AFJROTC cadets presented the colors.

Cindy Ross, her teacher and Braille aid, spoke about the true strength in character Sarah exhibits every day as she has learned to navigate her world while visually impaired. Sarah has grown to excel in the classroom as well as in her musical talent and quickly becoming a leader amongst her peers.

post_text:
These Little Commodores are becoming quite the budding scientists.

Students in Mrs. Goodwiller‚Äôs STEM Class are learning about how germs spread as well as how the use of soap and water can keep those germs from spreading.

The class simulated the spread of the flu by using regular water (healthy) and tonic water(not healthy). The tonic water glows under Blacklight allowing them to see the difference.

In the experiment, the Blacklight allowed students to see if they had the flu or not. Students used droppers and walked around the room to spread germs. The class started with two students having the flu and ended with nine when all students finished spreading their germs with the droppers.

These young scientists saw through a live experiment why it‚Äôs important to wash their hands.
